Problem Statement

Context

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations derived from this model

Key Takeaways - Shortlisting Candidates with Higher Chances of Visa Approval

These attributes have a more significant impact if:

  • Applicants possessing just a high school diploma have a higher rate of denials.
  • Prior work experience benefits the applicant to get its visa approved (the approval rate for the 14,802 applicants with work experience is 74.47%. Whereas, the approval rate for those without prior experience is 56.13%)
  • Master's Degree and Doctorate Degree holders exhibit a greater likelihood of approval (78.63% acceptance rate). Similarly, of the 2,192 Doctoral degree holders who applied, 1,912 were approved, representing an 87.23% acceptance rate, while the remaining 12.77% were denied.
  • Applicants from Europe exhibit a greater likelihood of approval.
  • Northeast, South and West regions exhibit high demand for foreign workers.

Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Strong profile for visa approval

  • Holds a university degree. Even stronger if possessing a Master's or Doctorate degree.
  • Has work experience.
  • Comes from a European country.
  • The intented work region is: Northeast, South, or West.

Weak Profile for Visa Approval

  • Possesses only a high school diploma.
  • Has no work experience.
  • Comes from a South American country.

Standardize wage according to work modality and payment frequency

In[]:
# New column to store "hours per year" considering if it is a full time job or not.
# 40 weekly hours * 52 (weeks in a year) = 2080 (full-time job)
# 35 weekly hours * 52 (weeks in a year) = 1820 (part-time job)
_data_copy['hours_per_year'] = _data_copy['full_time_position'].apply(lambda x: 2080 if x == 1 else 1820)

# Function to multiply each instance
def _to_yearly(_instance):
    if _instance['unit_of_wage'] == 'Hour':
        return _instance['hours_per_year']
    elif _instance['unit_of_wage'] == 'Week':
        return 52
    elif _instance['unit_of_wage'] == 'Month':
        return 12
    else:
        return 1  # Already yearly

_data_copy['wage_x_year'] = _data_copy.apply(_to_yearly, axis=1)
_data_copy['yearly_wage'] = _data_copy['prevailing_wage'] * _data_copy['wage_x_year']
_data_copy[['prevailing_wage', 'unit_of_wage', 'full_time_position', 'yearly_wage']].head()

Fit Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique - SMOTE - on train data

SMOTE parameters:

  • sampling_strategy = 1. Meaning: ratio of minority to majority class after resampling.

  • k_neighbors = 5. Meaning: how many nearest neighbors are used to generate synthetic samples. It picks one randomly and creates a new synthetic point between them.

  • random_state = 1.

  • x_train_over_sampled, y_train_over_sampled = fit_resample (x_train, y_train)

Model Building

Model Evaluation Criterion

Considering the following objectives:

  • Shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval.
  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Understand which attributes increase the likelihood of approval or rejection (both "certified" and "denied").

This case study requires identifying both false negatives (actual positive, predicted negative) being minimized = RECALL and, false positives (actual negative, predicted positive) being minimized = PRECISION.

Conclusion: the primary objective of this case study is to minimize both the number of applicants with a high probability of visa approval being predicted as "denied", and to minimize the number of applicants with a low probability of being approved being predicted as good candidates ("certified"). Therefore, F1-Score will be the principal metric. due to its balanced assessment of these two scenarios.

Observations

Six different models were developed based on the original dataset to evaluate multiple ensemble techniques. Three of these models implemented bagging methods; utilizing three different classifiers: "Decision Tree", "Bagging with decision trees as base estimators", and "Random Forest". The remaining three models, implemented boosting methods to evaluate the classifiers: "AdaBoost", "GradientBoost", and "XGBoost". All models were implemented with their default parameter settings, without hyperparameter tuning.

In this initial phase of model development, the primary focus will be on the F1-Score as the principal performance metric of the case study, along with the cross-validation score for each model.

The cross-validation score represents the average accuracy of the model across multiple data partitions, evaluating its overall performance in predicting both positive and negative instances.

For this analysis, the 'StratifiedKFold' function was used to preserve the ratio of different classes within each fold of the cross-validation process, considering 5 folds.

After identifying the optimal models, hyperparameter optimization will be performed, and a detailed analysis of all metrics will be conducted, confusion matrices will be generated, and a detailed comparative study of each model's performance will be undertaken.

Results of the models on the original dataset (without sampling or hyperparameter tuning):

  • Decision Tree, Bagging, and Random Forest models got overfitted.

  • The boosting models: AdaBoost, GradientBoost, and XGBoost, demonstrate good generalization.

  • GradientBoost is identified as the best-performing model, with an F1-Score of 0.8242 on the training set and, 0.8218 on the validation set.

  • Decision tree model: mean accuracy is 74% with a standard deviation of 0.73%. Such a lower standard deviation indicates that the model's accuracy is stable across different splits of the data; however, its mean accuracy is not appropriate. The model is consistently but not good enough.

  • AdaBoost model: mean accuracy is 81.8% with a standard deviation of 0.364%. The accuracy on any unseen data will lie between 81.09 and 82.51 with a confidence of 95% (avg +- 1.96 * std)

We have now tuned all the models, let's compare the performance of all tuned models and see which one is the best.

Observations:

  • Boosting models trained on the oversampled data got better performance and generalization. Consequently, all three models were subjected to hyperparameter tuning.

  • Furthermore, the Random Forest were also subjected to hyperparameter tuning in an attempt to identify hyperparameters that achieve better results.

AdaBoost with over sampled data:

  • Compared to the model with no tuning, this model got a slightly better F1-Score, both on training and validation sets
    • Model's scores without tuning: 0.805449 on training - 0.809818 on validation)
    • Model's scores with tuning: 0.831995 on training - 0.819331 on validation)
  • It is generalizing correctly.
  • Recall on training set was 0.8725 on training set and 0.8566 on validation set. Precision score is low, but F1-score is good.

Random Forest with under sampled data:

  • Compared to the model with no tuning, this model got a better F1-Score on validation set and overfitting is gone; but, it is still not good enough for this problem statement.
    • Model's scores without tuning: 1 on training - 0.725880 on validation)
    • Model's scores with tuning: 0.729933 on training - 0.778898 on validation)
  • Recall on training set was 0.7565 on training set and 0.7373 on validation set. Precision score is slightly better but still low (0.7050 on training and 0.8553 on validation).

Gradient boosting with oversampled data:

  • Compared to the model with no tuning, this model got a slightly better F1-Score, both on training and validation sets
    • Model's scores without tuning: 0.818541 on training - 0.817290 on validation)
    • Model's scores with tuning: 0.833404 on training - 0.818259 on validation)
  • It is generalizing correctly.
  • For this model, an AdaBoost classifier was utilized as the base estimator to generate initial predictions before the residual errors were adjusted by the boosting process. This approach enables the model to learn from the predictions generated by AdaBoost.

XGBoost using oversampled data

  • Achieve similar results to the model with no tuning. The primary difference is a reduced difference between the training and validation F1-scores.
    • Model's scores without tuning: 0.875105 on training -0.812369 on validation)
    • Model's scores with tuning: 0.825907 on training - 0.825216 on validation)

Observations:

In consideration of the following premises:

  • The primary objective of this case study is to minimize both the number of applicants with a high probability of visa approval being predicted as "denied", and to minimize the number of applicants with a low probability of being approved being predicted as good candidates ("certified") (with F1-Score serving as the principal due to its balanced assessment of these two scenarios).

  • Random Forest exhibited the lowest F1-Score on the training set (0.729933) and the validation set (0.778898) compared to the other models.

  • AdaBoost, Gradient Boost and XGBoost demonstrated better results on both the training set and validation sets relative to RandomForest. It can be affirmed that these models are generalizing well.

  • The performance of these three models is similar to each other. The main difference is that XGBoost showed a smaller difference between the training and validation score (0.000690).

  • XGBoost have the highest F1-Score observed on the validation set: 0.825216.

  • The GradientBoost model achieved a recall of 0.853114 on the validation set. XGBoost achieved a higher score = 0.896005. There is a considerable difference between them

  • The validation set precision for GradientBoost is 0.786140. And 0.764794 for XGBoost. The difference is not determining.

Final decision:

Therefore, considering these factors, the XGBoost model with oversampled data is considered the optimal choice.

In[]:
# Case_status =  1 probabilities
_y_metrics_results = _tuned_xgb.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# get precision, recall and AUC-PR
_precision, _recall, _thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, _y_metrics_results)
_auc_pr = auc(_recall, _precision)

_f1_scores = 2 * (_precision * _recall) / (_precision + _recall + 1e-10)
_best_index = np.argmax(_f1_scores)  # Index with higher F1-score

_best_precision = _precision[_best_index]
_best_recall = _recall[_best_index]
_best_threshold = _thresholds[_best_index]

  • Their current continent of residence.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

Key Takeaways - Shortlisting Candidates with Higher Chances of Visa Approval

These attributes have a more significant impact if:

  • Applicants possessing just a high school diploma have a higher rate of denials.
  • Prior work experience benefits the applicant to get its visa approved (the approval rate for the 14,802 applicants with work experience is 74.47%. Whereas, the approval rate for those without prior experience is 56.13%)
  • Master's Degree and Doctorate Degree holders exhibit a greater likelihood of approval (78.63% acceptance rate). Similarly, of the 2,192 Doctoral degree holders who applied, 1,912 were approved, representing an 87.23% acceptance rate, while the remaining 12.77% were denied.
  • Applicants from Europe exhibit a greater likelihood of approval.
  • Northeast, South and West regions exhibit high demand for foreign workers.

Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Strong profile for visa approval

  • Holds a university degree. Even stronger if possessing a Master's or Doctorate degree.
  • Has work experience.
  • Comes from a European country.
  • The intented work region is: Northeast, South, or West.

Weak Profile for Visa Approval

  • Possesses only a high school diploma.
  • Has no work experience.
  • Comes from a South American country.
